🟦 Entry Modes: Adapting to User Needs

The Legal Calculus Educational System (LCES) recognizes that people enter the legal process for different reasons.

Some need education.

Some need urgent action.

Some need review.

Some need protection.

That is why LCES supports four primary entry modes.

Each mode runs on the same core framework—but the priority structure shifts based on the user’s immediate need.

🔹 1. Pro Se Mode

Built for self-represented users navigating active legal problems.

Priority focus:

- 📌 Issue isolation

• 🛡️ Preservation of rights

• ⚠️ Avoiding waiver

• 📂 Building a usable record

Goal: move from confusion to controlled action.

🔹 2. Education Mode

Designed for learning how legal systems function.

Priority focus:

- 📚 Procedural literacy

• 🧠 Role clarity

• 🗺️ Doctrine maps

• 📄 Filing sequences

Success means understanding how to frame issues and read the record.

🔹 3. Second-Opinion Mode

For users who already have a draft or strategy and need review before filing.

Priority focus:

- 🔍 Structural review

• ⏱️ Sequencing review

• 🧾 Preservation review

• 🛠️ Detecting hidden defects

Here, the Inspector role becomes central.

🔹 4. Crisis Mode

For time-compressed situations where immediate action is required.

Priority focus:

- 🚨 Rapid triage

• 🎯 One defensible next step

• 📉 Narrowing scope

• ❌ Minimizing avoidable error

Goal: move from disorder to action fast.

🟨 The core insight:

Different legal moments require different priorities.

The same framework can educate, stabilize, inspect, or accelerate—depending on what the user needs most.

⚖️ LCES adapts to reality, not theory.

